sentences: Carney was born on April 1, 1910, in Boston, Massachusetts.
After playing a variety of gigs in New York City at the age of 17, Carney was invited to join the Duke Ellington band for its performances in Boston in 1927.
After Ellington added more personnel in 1928, Carney's main instrument became the baritone saxophone.
In January 1938, Carney was invited to play with Benny Goodman's band at Carnegie Hall.
Recordings from this event were released as The Famous 1938 Carnegie Hall Jazz Concert.
Carney also took up the bass clarinet around 1944.
In 1957, Carney was part of a band led by pianist Billy Taylor that recorded the album Taylor Made Jazz.
In 1973 Ellington built the Third Sacred Concert around Carney's baritone saxophone.
After Ellington's 1974 death, Carney said: "Without Duke I have nothing to live for".
Four months after Ellington's death, Carney also died, on October 8, 1974, in New York.

sentences: Harry Howell Carney (April 1, 1910 – October 8, 1974) was a jazz saxophonist and clarinettist who spent over four decades as a member of the Duke Ellington Orchestra.
Carney began by playing the piano at age seven, moved to the clarinet at 14, and added the alto saxophone a year later.
He soon recorded with Ellington too, with a first session in October that year.
The band began a residency at the Cotton Club in New York at the end of the year.
Four months after Ellington's death, Carney also died, on October 8, 1974, in New York.
